To create a Visual Studio Code extension that opens a Google window within VS Code, you would typically create a WebView that loads the Google homepage. Below are the steps and code examples to achieve this, broken down into the `extension.ts` and `package.json` files.

Firstly, you'd set up the VS Code extension scaffold if you haven't yet:

1. Run `npm install -g yo generator-code` to install Yeoman and the VS Code extension generator.
2. Run `yo code` to create a new extension and follow the prompts.
3. When prompted for the type of extension, select `New Extension (TypeScript)`.

After you've set that up, modify the generated `extension.ts` file and create the `package.json` file accordingly:

`extension.ts`:
```typescript
import * as vscode from 'vscode';

export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
    context.subscriptions.push(
        vscode.commands.registerCommand('extension.openGoogle', () => {
            // Create and show a new webview
            const panel = vscode.window.createWebviewPanel(
                'googleWebview', // Identifies the type of the webview. Used internally
                'Google', // Title of the panel displayed to the user
                vscode.ViewColumn.One, // Editor column to show the new webview panel in.
                { 
                    // Enable scripts in the webview
                    enableScripts: true
                }
            );

            // And set its HTML content
            panel.webview.html = getGoogleWebViewContent();
        })
    );
}

function getGoogleWebViewContent() {
    return `
        <!DOCTYPE html>
        <html lang="en">
        <head>
            <meta charset="UTF-8">
            <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
            <title>Google</title>
        </head>
        <body>
            <iframe src="https://www.google.com" frameborder="0" style="width:100%; height:100vh;"></iframe>
        </body>
        </html>
    `;
}

export function deactivate() {}
```

`package.json`:
```json
