In the context of a binary search tree (BST) and a postorder traversal, if you want to count the values at each point (i.e., the number of nodes in the subtree of each node), you will have to perform a modification of the traditional postorder traversal algorithm.

Here's an example of a TypeScript class that represents a node in a BST, and a function that performs a postorder traversal while counting the nodes:

```typescript
class TreeNode {
    value: number;
    left: TreeNode | null;
    right: TreeNode | null;

    constructor(value: number) {
        this.value = value;
        this.left = null;
        this.right = null;
    }
}

function countNodes(root: TreeNode | null): number {
    if (root === null) { return 0; }

    // Count nodes in the left subtree
    const leftCount = countNodes(root.left);
    // Count nodes in the right subtree
    const rightCount = countNodes(root.right);

    // Count the current node
    const total = 1 + leftCount + rightCount; 

    // Here you might want to do something with the count, for example, print it.
    console.log(`Node with value ${root.value} has ${total} node(s) in its subtree.`);

    return total;
}

// Example Usage
const root = new TreeNode(10);
root.left = new TreeNode(5);
root.right = new TreeNode(15);
root.left.left = new TreeNode(3);
root.left.right = new TreeNode(7);
root.right.right = new TreeNode(18);

countNodes(root); // This will perform the traversal and count the nodes
```

This script defines a `TreeNode` class with `value`, `left`, and `right` properties, where `left` and `right` are the left and right children of the node, respectively, or `null` if there are no children. The `countNodes` function performs a recursive postorder traversal: first, it processes the left subtree, then the right subtree, and finally the current node itself. At each step, it counts the total number of nodes in the subtree rooted at the current node.

Keep in mind that the presented `countNodes` function will visit each node exactly once, resulting in a time complexity of O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the tree. As it visits each node, it calculates the size of the subtree using the postorder traversal count from its left and right children (if they exist).

If you wish to sum the values in the nodes of a binary search tree (BST) starting from the leaves, you can implement a postorder traversal. During postorder traversal, you visit the node after you've visited its left and right subtrees. This ensures that you work from the leaves towards the root.

Here's an example of a TypeScript function to perform a postorder traversal on a BST and return the sum of all the node values, starting with the leaves and moving up to the root:

```typescript
class TreeNode {
    value: number;
    left: TreeNode | null;
    right: TreeNode | null;

    constructor(value: number) {
        this.value = value;
        this.left = null;
        this.right = null;
    }
}

function postorderSum(root: TreeNode | null): number {
    if (root === null) {
        return 0; // Base case: if the node is null, return 0
    }

    // Recurse on the left and right subtrees
    const leftSum = postorderSum(root.left);
    const rightSum = postorderSum(root.right);

    // Sum of the current node and its subtrees
    const totalSum = root.value + leftSum + rightSum;

    // Instead of printing, you can do another operation with totalSum if needed.
    console.log(`The total sum at node with value ${root.value} is ${totalSum}.`);

    // Return the sum up the call stack
    return totalSum;
}

// Example Usage
const root = new TreeNode(10);
root.left = new TreeNode(5);
root.right = new TreeNode(15);
root.left.left = new TreeNode(3);
root.left.right = new TreeNode(7);
root.right.right = new TreeNode(18);

const totalSum = postorderSum(root);
console.log(`The sum of all nodes in the BST is ${totalSum}.`);
```

In this code, `postorderSum` is a recursive function that:

1. Returns 0 if the current node is `null` (base case).
2. Recursively calls itself to sum the values of the left and right subtrees.
3. Adds the value of the current node to the sums obtained from its left and right children.
4. Prints the total sum at the current node (for demonstration).
5. Returns the sum value up the call stack.

This function visits each node exactly once, giving it a time complexity of O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the BST. It will compute and print the sum of the values from the leaves up to the root node.

