The function `findLargestBST` has two logic problems:

Firstly, it is extremely inefficient because it invokes `findLargestBST` multiple times recursively without memorizing results (which leads to an exponential time algorithm). Each call to `isBST` traverses the entire subtree, and this is being done repeatedly for the same nodes.

Secondly, there is a flaw in the range check within `isBST`. If a tree node has the same value as one of its ancestors (which is the case in your input sequence), such a tree cannot be a BST by definition because BST requires that all values in the left subtree be strictly less than the node's value, and all values in the right subtree be strictly greater.

To solve these issues, you should restructure the algorithm to avoid repeated calculations, and you should also correctly determine the largest BST within the tree.

Here is a revised version of `findLargestBST` that includes a helper function to recursively find the largest BST and to ensure that the conditions for BST are met. Also, it computes the size of the largest BST so far as it goes, avoiding unnecessary repeated function calls. I've also fixed the logic challenge you are seeing:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <climits>
#include <algorithm>

struct Node {
    Node* left = nullptr;
    Node* right = nullptr;
    Node* parent = nullptr;
    int profit = 0;
};

struct Info {
    int size;       // Size of the subtree
    bool isBST;     // Is the subtree a BST
    int minProfit;  // Minimum profit in the subtree
    int maxProfit;  // Maximum profit in the subtree
};

Info getLargestBSTsubtreeHelper(Node* root) {
    // A null node is a BST of size 0
    if (root == nullptr) {
        return {0, true, INT_MAX, INT_MIN};
    }

    // Postorder traversal: left -> right -> node
    Info leftInfo = getLargestBSTsubtreeHelper(root->left);
    Info rightInfo = getLargestBSTsubtreeHelper(root->right);

    Info currInfo;
    if (leftInfo.isBST && rightInfo.isBST && 
        root->profit > leftInfo.maxProfit && root->profit < rightInfo.minProfit) {
        // It is a BST.
        currInfo.size = leftInfo.size + rightInfo.size + 1;
        currInfo.isBST = true;
    } else {
        // It is not a BST.
        currInfo.size = std::max(leftInfo.size, rightInfo.size); // Take the larger of the two
        currInfo.isBST = false;
    }

    currInfo.minProfit = std::min(root->profit, leftInfo.minProfit);
    currInfo.maxProfit = std::max(root->profit, rightInfo.maxProfit);

    return currInfo;
}

int findLargestBST(Node* root) {
    return getLargestBSTsubtreeHelper(root).size;
}

// Your original input handling code can go here.

int main() {
    // ... original input handling code ...
    std::cout << findLargestBST(root);
    return 0;
}
```

